            <h3>Guidelines for Authors</h3>
            
            <p align="justify">The journal invites the submission of original unpublished works which are not submitted to any other  journals or under consideration by other journals. It is understood that an author agrees exclusive copyright to Asian Journal of Research Scholars. Asian Journal of Research Scholars which expects high scientific standards. All submitted papers will therefore will be sent for double-blind refereeing process. Authors are !00% responsible for their manuscripts and the editor does not accept any responsibility for the copyright issues if any received in future. So that, authors are asked to check twice before submitting their work. Author and co-authors are responsible for any statement or opinion in the articles and the editorial board disclaims legal responsibility for any assertion, opinion or interpretation of the author. </p>
            
        
        </div>
        <div class="learning_member_text">
            
            <h3>Guidelines for Editors</h3>
            
            <p align="justify">Editors are to evaluate the suitability of submitted manuscripts for the journal, including: (a) the standard of the manuscript, (b) whether it meets the Aims and Scope of the journal (Of course ours is a multidisciplinary journal), and (c) the originality of the work. The editors will never disclose the information about a submitted manuscript to anyone other than the corresponding author, reviewers or potential reviewers, or other members of the editorial board. Editors will ensure the prompt handling of the review process and will evaluate the merit of manuscripts for intellectual content without regard to race, gender, country of origin, ethnicity, religion, or sexual orientation.</p>
            
        
        </div>
        <div class="learning_member_text">
            
            <h3>Guidelines for Reviewers</h3>
            
            <p align="justify">Peer review is essential to the journal in assisting in making editorial decisions and assisting authors in manuscript improvement. Reviewers should point out relevant publications not cited in the manuscript and point out any similarities with previously published works. Also, our technical staff will execute the instructions given by the reviewers in the prescribed format. If a potential reviewer feels unfamiliar in an area to review the manuscript, that reviewer should notify the editors immediately and decline the review. Manuscripts received for review will be treated as confidential documents and not shown or discussed with other without authorization from the editors. Authors should expect to receive reviewer reports in a prompt manner, normally within three weeks. Reviewers are expected to be genuine and should never breach of confidentiality, delay of peer review, plagiarism, or conflicts of interest</p>
            
        
        </div>
        <div class="learning_member_text">
            
            <h3>Guidelines for Publishers</h3>
            
            <p align="justify">
                All manuscripts will be subjected to a standard anonymous peer review process before acceptance. The editorial board will send the copy of reviewer’s anonymous report, and the authors should carry out or respond in accordance with the suggestions received in the report.  After receiving the response, the manuscript will be approved. The editorial board reserves the right to reject any original work that they consider to be unsuitable or the manuscript which is outside the focus of the journal. The letters to the editor through email shall be answered and approved directly by the editor, upon the reports from the editorial board. Authors, who consider an urgent publication,           should specify this in their covering letter, including an appropriate justification. Based on the editorial board’s recommendation, such works shall undergo a priority review process. Every author/s is/are responsible for the statements and opinions expressed in the articles, including possible errors or falseness. In cases of proven plagiarism or fraudulent publication, the publisher is empowered to carry out appropriate action to avoid controversies by publishing erratum or , in collaboration with the editorial board, will take appropriate action to clarify the situation, publish an erratum, or withdraw the work in controversy.
            </p>
            
        
        </div>
        <div class="learning_member_text">
            
            <h3>Guidelines for Submission </h3>
            
            <p align="justify">
                Authors of original research work (not previously published or under consideration for publication elsewhere) should be an accurate presentation of the work carried out. Appropriate citation of previously published works must always be included in the works cited. Financial support if any should be disclosed. Authorship should be limited to four authors to those persons who have made a significant contribution to the work in terms of conception, design, experimental implementation, and data analysis or typing and editing. All persons making significant contributions should be included as co-authors. Of course, an English Language Teacher or any other language expert is permitted as a co-author even in technical subjects. It is unethical to copy, plagiarize, manipulate or giving fake data in a manuscript. After considering all the above concerns, authors are asked to use our “Submit Online” option in our journal’s to submit a manuscript.  Authors are asked to fill up the title of the paper, name of the author (s), institution address, affiliation and email  of the corresponding author exactly. 
                The authors are asked to pay the publication fee of Rs.1500/- (upto four authors) to 
